al story, Island World rejects the premise that continents comprise "natural" states while islands are "tiny spaces," without significance, to be acted upon by continents. An astonishingly compact tour de force, this book not only revises the way we think about islands, oceans, and continents, it also recasts the way we write about space and time.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMarine ecology. 0aWhalesxEcology. 0aWhalingxEnvironmental aspects. 4aHistory. 4aWorld. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh1 aOkihiro, Gary Y., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026167940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093419140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520934191423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520934191/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles